Scanner‘s hasNextLine() method checks if there is another line in the input, no matter if the line is blank or not, while hasNext() uses a delimiter to check for another token. using hasNext() might solve your problem. check this for more info [hasNext() vs hasNextLine()][1] 

However, you are using Scanner class&#39;s nextLine() to get the total number of lines. This can be efficient for small to medium-sized files, but may not be suitable for very large files that cannot fit into memory. 

    public static long countLines(String file) {
    try {
        return Files.lines(Paths.get(file)).parallel().count();
    } catch (IOException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
        return -1;
    }
}


This method uses the parallel() method to create a parallel stream of lines, which can improve performance for large files by using multiple threads to process the lines in parallel.


