answers.body_markdown:
Because most operations on `BigInteger` are themselves `O(n)`, assuming the size of the BI instance is itself growing linear to `n`.

For example:

```
int a = 5;
int b = 10;
int c = a + b;
```

The above code is, rather obviously, `O(1)`. However,

```
BigInteger a = ....;
BigInteger b = ....;
BigInteger c = a.add(b);
```

The above code is all on its own `O(n)`! At least, assuming the sizes of a and b are linear to `n`, which they generally are, if BigInteger is required for the algorithm to work.

There&#39;s no quick fix for any of this. You need a completely different algorithm, most likely. &quot;Just make BigInt ops be O(1)&quot; is about as sensible as &quot;Just calculate this NP-hard problem with a simple for loop please&quot;.

